'''Kashima Shrine''' ('''Kashima Shrine''', かしまじんじゃ) is a {{jalink|Shinto shrine|Q845945}} in Shimoda-nishi, {{jalink|Kashiba|Q696643}}, {{jalink|Nara Prefecture|Q131287}}.

It is the shrine from which the name of Kashiba City is said to derive<ref name="city-name">[https://www.city.kashiba.lg.jp/soshiki/5/3826.html 香芝市の沿革] - Kashiba City</ref>.

=== Overview ===
It is enshrined near west of JR {{jalink|Kashiba Station|Q3655907}}, and near north of {{jalink|Kintetsu Shimoda Station|Q6414373}} on the {{jalink|Kintetsu Osaka Line|Q1052545}}.

Its founding is said to begin in March {{jalink|1172|Q19687}} ({{jalink|Shōan (Japan)|Q1194188|Shōan}} 2), when {{jalink|Kamada Masamitsu}}, son of {{jalink|Kamada Masakiyo|Q11651065}} (a retainer of {{jalink|Minamoto no Yoshitomo|Q532301}}), invited the deity from {{jalink|Kashima Jingū|Q706499}} in {{jalink|Hitachi Province|Q1055353}} (present-day {{jalink|Ibaraki Prefecture|Q83273}})<ref name="yuisho">[https://kashiba-no-kashima.org/top-page/history/ 由緒] - Kashima Shrine</ref><ref name="city-muse">[https://www.city.kashiba.lg.jp/uploaded/attachment/1653.pdf 鹿島神社] - Kashiba Nijō-san Museum</ref>.

There is also a theory that before the founding of this Kashima Shrine, an older local shrine existed here, namely '''Fukamizo Shrine''', one of the {{jalink|Shikinaisha in Yamato Province|Q11433427|Shikinaisha of Yamato Province}}<ref name="yuisho"/><ref name="city-muse"/>.

=== Enshrined deity ===
* {{jalink|Takemikazuchi-no-Ōkami}}

